'''Jamal Musiala''' ({{IPA|de|ˈdʒaːmal muˈzi̯aːla|-|}}; born 26 February 2003) is a German professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] for {{German football updater|BaMunich}} club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] and the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]]. Widely regarded as one of the best attacking midfielders in the world,<ref>{{Cite web |first1 = Mark | last1 = White | first2 = Isaac | last2 = Stacey Stronge | first3 = Joe | last3 = Mewis | first4 = Steven | last4 = Chicken | first5 = Matthew | last5 = Holt | date = 16 June 2025 |title = Ranked! The 10 best attacking midfielders in the world |url = https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/ranked-best-attacking-midfielders-in-the-world | access-date = 26 October 2025 | website = FourFourTwo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date = 4 June 2025 |title = 2025 FC 100: Bellingham among best attacking midfielders in men's soccer |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/45178766/2025-fc-100-bellingham-best-attacking-midfielders-mens-soccer |access-date=22 September 2025 |website=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=22 July 2025 |title=The 25 Best Attacking Midfielders in World Soccer: Ranked |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/the-best-attacking-midfielders-in-world-soccer-ranked |access-date=22 September 2025 |website=SI}}</ref> Musiala is known for his [[dribbling]], passing, goal threat, and technical skills, and is nicknamed "[[Bambi (character)|Bambi]]" for his close-control dribbling.<ref name=":2">{{cite web |title=Jamal Musiala |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/player/jamal-musiala |access-date=23 September 2024 |publisher=Bundesliga}}</ref>

Musiala has represented Germany at [[UEFA Euro 2020]], the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], and [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]]. He was the joint winner of Euro 2024's [[UEFA European Championship awards#Top goalscorer|Golden Boot]].

==Early life==
Musiala was born in [[Stuttgart]], Germany, to his Nigerian-British father Daniel Richard and German mother with [[Poles in Germany|Polish]] roots {{citation needed|date=August 2025}}, Carolin Musiala.<ref>{{cite news|date=24 February 2021|title=Jamal Musiala: Bayern Munich youngster picks Germany over England at international level|website=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56176585|access-date=25 February 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hau |first=Kerry |title= THE MAKING OF JAMAL MUSIALA |url=https://www.goal.com/story/the-making-of-jamal-musiala/index.html |access-date=8 December 2021|website=Goal.com}}</ref> He lived in [[Fulda]] until the age of seven, before moving to England with his family, where he remained for the rest of his childhood.<ref name="whois">{{Cite web|title=Jamal Musiala: Who is Bayern Munich's half-English, half-German star of the future?|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/who-is-jamal-musiala-bayern-munich-s-half-england-germany-star-of-the-future-11525|access-date=19 July 2020|publisher=Bundesliga}}</ref><ref name="NovemberGoal">{{cite news |title=Bayern wonderkid Musiala 'sees his future' with England amid international tussle with Germany |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/bayern-wonderkid-musiala-sees-his-future-with-england-amid/1n0bofp7ggojr16c8jupqeejg9 |access-date=25 February 2021 |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=12 November 2020}}</ref> He went to [[primary school]] at the Corpus Christi School in [[New Malden]], and represented the school on behalf of a succession of local football clubs, including [[Fulham FC|Fulham]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Schools Champions|url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2013/may/21/schools-champions|access-date=21 May 2013|publisher=Fulham FC}}</ref> [[Brentford FC|Brentford]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=When Musiala played at Wembley 10 years ago in Utilita Kids Cup Final|date=14 June 2024 |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2024/june/14/when-musiala-played-at-wembley-10-years-ago-in-utilita-kids-cup-final/|access-date=14 June 2024|publisher=EFL}}</ref> and [[AFC Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] in the [[English Football League|EFL]] Utilita Kids Cup, winning the competition twice.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Wembley glory for boys|url=https://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/news/2014/may/wembley-glory-for-boys/|access-date=19 July 2020|publisher=AFC Wimbledon | date = 27 May 2014 | first = Chris | last = Slavin}}</ref> For [[secondary school]], he went to the [[Whitgift School]] in [[Croydon]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=PROSPECT {{!}} Jamal Musiala | url = https://www.getfootballnewsgermany.com/2020/prospect-jamal-musiala/ | access-date = 19 July 2020 |website=Get German Football News| date = 12 June 2020 }}</ref> He was in the [[Chelsea F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Chelsea academy]] for the last years of his childhood. Musiala has played for both Germany and England national teams at youth level, and eventually pledged his allegiance to the [[German Football Association]] for future games in February 2021.<ref name="whois"/> At the age of 16, Musiala and his mother returned to Germany for personal reasons and the impending [[Brexit]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 February 2021 |title=Der Ex-Lehnerzer Jamal Musiala startet beim FC Bayern München durch |url=https://www.fuldaerzeitung.de/fulda/jamal-musiala-fc-bayern-muenchen-lehnerz-talent-durchbruch-champions-league-13656624.html |access-date=20 June 2024 |website=www.fuldaerzeitung.de |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Brown |first=Oliver |date=15 June 2024 |title=Germany's new talisman is Jamal Musiala – the one that got away for England |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2024/06/15/germany-talisman-jamal-musiala-euro-2024-england/ |access-date=25 June 2024 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Collins |first=David |date=25 June 2024 |title=Brexit to blame for England losing Jamal Musiala to Germany |url=https://www.thetimes.com/uk/politics/article/brexit-to-blame-for-england-losing-jamal-musiala-to-germany-q70nmlq5z |access-date=25 June 2024 |website=[[The Times]]|language=en}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Bayern Munich===
====2019–20: Debut season====
In July 2019, aged 16, Musiala left [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] to join [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]].<ref name="bundesliga">{{cite web | url = https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-sign-chelsea-teenagers-jamal-musiala-bright-arrey-mbi-england-germany-5437 | title = Bayern Munich sign 16-year-old Chelsea talents Jamal Musiala and Bright Arrey-Mbi |publisher=Bundesliga | date = 2 July 2019 | access-date = 5 June 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kollmann|first=Steffen|date=29 February 2020|title=Der Ex-Lehnerzer Jamal Musiala startet beim FC Bayern München durch|url=https://www.fuldaerzeitung.de/fulda/ex-lehnerzer-jamal-musiala-startet-beim-bayern-muenchen-durch-13656624.html|access-date=13 December 2020|language=de|newspaper=Fuldaer Zeitung}}</ref> On 3 June 2020, Musiala made his professional debut, coming on as a substitute for [[FC Bayern Munich II|Bayern Munich II]] in their 3–2 win over [[SC Preußen Münster|Preußen Münster]] in the [[3. Liga]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2020/06/03/germany/3-liga/fc-bayern-munchen-ii/sc-preussen-06-ev-munster/3053420/ |title=Bayern München II vs. Preußen Münster 3–2: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=25 February 2021}}</ref> On 20 June 2020, he made his Bundesliga debut against [[SC Freiburg]], and he became the youngest player to play a match for Bayern in the Bundesliga, aged 17 years and 115 days.<ref>{{Cite web|date=20 June 2020|title=Jamal Musiala: Jüngster Bundesliga-Debütant des FC Bayern|url=https://fcbayern.com/de/news/2020/06/jamal-musiala-juengster-bundesliga-debuetant-des-fc-bayern|access-date=8 August 2020|publisher=FC Bayern Munich|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=21 June 2020|title=Fünf Bayern-Talente feierten diese Saison ihr Bundesliga-Debüt|url=https://fcbayern.com/de/news/2020/06/fuenf-bayern-talente-feierten-diese-saison-ihr-bundesliga-debuet|access-date=8 August 2020|publisher=FC Bayern Munich|language=de}}</ref>
Musiala was a part of the squad that won the [[2019–20 UEFA Champions League]], although he did not make any appearances in the tournament.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53867676 | title = Paris St-Germain 0-1 Bayern Munich: German Side win Champions League | work = BBC Sport | access-date = 13 September 2022}}</ref>

====2020–21: First-team breakthrough====
On 18 September 2020, Musiala scored his first Bundesliga goal in an 8–0 win over [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke]], to become Bayern's youngest goalscorer, aged 17 years and 205 days, breaking the previous record of [[Roque Santa Cruz]], aged 18 years and 12 days.<ref name="whois" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54213163 |title=Bayern Munich 8–0 FC Schalke 04 |website=BBC Sport |date=18 September 2020 | access-date = 18 September 2020}}</ref> On 3 November, Musiala made his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut as a substitute to [[Thomas Müller]] in a 6–2 away win over [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/matchreports/2020/11/match-report-champions-league-red-bull-salzburg-v-fc-bayern-031120 |title=Resolute Reds down battling Salzburg |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=3 November 2020 }}</ref> On 1 December, he started in his first Champions League match in a 1–1 away draw against [[Atlético Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/dec/02/jamal-musiala-shines-for-bayern-munich-champions-league-atletico-madrid |title=Jamal Musiala shines for Bayern with flashing feet, touch and tackles |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 December 2020 }}</ref> On 23 February 2021, Musiala scored his first Champions League goal in a 4–1 away win over [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] in the first leg of the round of 16 tie of the knockout phase, becoming the competition's youngest goalscorer of both English and German nationalities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lazio 1-4 Bayern Munich: Jamal Musiala becomes youngest English scorer|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56158031 |access-date=23 February 2021 |website=BBC Sport |date=23 February 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Musiala toppt alle: Die jüngsten deutschen CL-Torschützen|url=https://www.kicker.de/musiala-toppt-alle-die-juengsten-deutschen-cl-torschuetzen-791168/slideshow|access-date=24 February 2021 |website=kicker |publisher=Olympia-Verlag |date=24 February 2021}}</ref> He also became Bayern's youngest goalscorer in the European competition, aged 17 years and 363 days, breaking previous record by [[Samuel Kuffour]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/jamal-musiala-becomes-bayern-munich-s-youngest-champions-league-goalscorer-14889 |title=Jamal Musiala becomes Bayern Munich's youngest UEFA Champions League goalscorer |publisher=Bundesliga |date=February 2021 }}</ref> On 5 March, he signed his first professional contract with Bayern Munich until 2026.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2021/03/pm-musiala |title=Musiala signs until 2026 |website=Bayern Munich|date=5 March 2021 }}</ref>

====2021–2023: Continuous development and Bundesliga title decider====
[[File:2022-07-30 Fußball, Männer, DFL-Supercup, RB Leipzig - FC Bayern München 1DX 3417 by Stepro (Jamal Musiala, Joshua Zikzee).jpg|thumb|upright|Musiala celebrating the win of the 2022 [[DFL-Supercup]]]]
On 25 August 2021, Musiala scored his first two goals of the season in a 12–0 [[DFB-Pokal]] away win over [[Bremer SV]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Choupo-Moting nets four as Bayern Munich score 12 against Bremer SV |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bremer-sv-bayern-munich-dfb-cup-live-line-ups-stats-lewandowski-davies-sane-17021 |access-date=24 April 2022 |publisher=Bundesliga}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Bayern put 12 past Bremer SV in cup win |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58335764 |access-date=24 April 2022}}</ref> Three days later, he then scored his first Bundesliga goal of the season in a 5–0 home win over [[Hertha BSC]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Lewandowski grabs hat-trick as records tumble |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58372161 |access-date=24 April 2022}}</ref> On 8 December 2021, Musiala scored his first Champions League goal of the season in a 3–0 win over [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Barcelona out of Champions League |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59587194 |access-date=24 April 2022}}</ref> On 23 April 2022, Musiala's strike sealed the Bundesliga title in a 3–1 victory over [[Borussia Dortmund]] in [[Der Klassiker]], giving Bayern their tenth straight Bundesliga title.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bosher |first=Luke |title=Bayern Munich win 10th consecutive Bundesliga title after victory over Borussia Dortmund |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4179529/2022/04/22/bayern-munich-win-10th-consecutive-bundesliga-title-after-victory-over-borussia-dortmund/ |access-date=24 April 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Bayern seal 10th straight Bundesliga title |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61204767 |access-date=24 April 2022}}</ref><ref name="bundesliga.com">{{Cite web |title=Unstoppable Bayern Munich make it 10 Bundesliga titles on the bounce with Klassiker win over Borussia Dortmund |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-borussia-dortmund-live-team-news-match-stats-lewandowski-haaland-19611 |access-date=24 April 2022 |publisher=Bundesliga}}</ref>

On 27 May 2023, Musiala scored the winning goal in the 89th minute in a 2–1 away victory over [[1. FC Köln|FC Köln]]. This goal clinched the 11th consecutive league title for his club again ahead of rivals Dortmund on goal difference.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bayern-munich-champions-again-after-dortmund-meltdown/a-65753627 |title=Bayern Munich champions again after Dortmund meltdown |publisher=DW |date=27 May 2023 }}</ref> Moreover, he finished the season as Bayern's second top scorer in the league with 12 goals, behind [[Serge Gnabry]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/jamal-musiala-i-didnt-think-about-it-i-just-celebrated-37567210 |title=Jamal Musiala: "I didn't think about it, I just celebrated." |publisher=OneFootball |date=27 May 2023 }}</ref>

====2024–present: Contract extension, injury and comeback ====
In the [[2023–24 FC Bayern Munich season|2023–24 season]], Musiala scored 13 goals in all competitions, including 10 goals in Bundesliga, concluding the campaign as the second top scorer for his club behind [[Harry Kane]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/jamal-musiala-how-germanys-future-messi-can-take-euro-2024-by-storm-39608372 |title=Jamal Musiala: How Germany's 'future Messi' can take Euro 2024 by storm |publisher=OneFootball |date=10 June 2024 }}</ref> On 30 October 2024, he scored his first career [[Hattrick (football)|hat-trick]] in a 4–0 away victory over [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz]] in the [[2024–25 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dailysports.net/news/a-historic-day-jamal-musiala-scored-the-first-hattrick-of-his-career/ |title=A historic day. Jamal Musiala scored the first hat-trick of his career |publisher=Dailysports.net |date=30 October 2024 }}</ref> On 14 February 2025, he extended his contract with Bayern until 2030.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2025/02/jamal-musiala-signs-contract-extension-with-fc-bayern-to-2030 |title=Jamal Musiala signs contract extension with FC Bayern |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=14 February 2025 }}</ref> Later that year, on 15 June, he scored another hat-trick including a first career [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] in a 10–0 win against [[Auckland City FC|Auckland City]] during the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup]], becoming the first ever player in the new [[FIFA Club World Cup|CWC]] format to score a hattrick and reaching his personal best by netting his 20th goal of the season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mentruit |first=Inma |url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/us/en/20250615/724586/10-0-ruthless-bayern-dominate-auckland-in-debut-as-musiala-returns-with-hat-trick.html |title=10-0: Ruthless Bayern dominate Auckland in debut as Musiala Returns with a hat trick |publisher=Mundo Deportivo |date=15 June 2025 }}</ref> He later acquired the number 10 shirt, succeeding [[Leroy Sané]], ahead of the 2025–26 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2025/07/musiala-to-wear-the-number-ten-jersey |title=Jamal Musiala to wear number 10 after Club World Cup |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=1 July 2025 }}</ref> On 5 July 2025, he suffered a fractured fibula along with a dislocated and broken ankle after colliding with [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Donnarumma]] during the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup knockout stage#Paris Saint-Germain vs Bayern Munich|quarter-finals of the 2025 FIFA Club World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/news/2025/07/jamal-musiala-diagnosis |title=Jamal Musiala sidelined for long period |publisher=FC Bayern Munich |date=6 July 2025 }}</ref> After 196 days, he would return to the pitch on 17 January 2026, getting subbed on for [[Serge Gnabry]] in the 88th minute, and immediately assisting to [[Michael Olise]] after 76 seconds to help his team win 5–1 over [[RB Leipzig]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 January 2026 |title=RB Leipzig - FC Bayern München 17.01.2026 (Spielbericht) |url=https://fcbayern.com/de/spiele/profis/bundesliga/2025-2026/rb-leipzig-fc-bayern-muenchen-17-01-2026/spielbericht |url-status=live |access-date=5 April 2026 |website=FC Bayern}}</ref> He celebrated his return to the starting line-up twelve days later on 29 January in the [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], scoring a goal after a beautiful combination play with [[Lennart Karl]] in a 2–1 away victory over [[PSV Eindhoven|Eindhoven]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 January 2026 |title=Tor bei Startelf Rückkehr - demütiger Musiala feiert Märchen Comeback |url=https://sport.sky.de/fussball/artikel/tor-bei-startelf-rueckkehr-demuetiger-musiala-feiert-maerchen-comeback/13500404/33896 |url-status=live |access-date=5 April 2026 |website=Sky Sport Deutschland}}</ref> On 6 March, he scored his first goal of the [[2025–26 Bundesliga|Bundesliga season]] from a penalty kick in a 4–1 home victory over [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=sportschau.de |title=Musiala trifft bei Bayern Münchens deutlichem Sieg gegen Gladbach |url=https://www.sportschau.de/fussball/bundesliga/fc-bayern-rotiert-und-siegt-locker-gegen-gladbach,spielbericht-bayern-muenchen-borussia-moenchengladbach-114.html |access-date=5 April 2026 |website=sportschau.de |language=de}}</ref> Four days later in the first leg of the Champions League round of 16, he scored his second goal of the competition's season in a 6–1 away victory over [[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]], injuring his previously broken ankle again,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Montazeri |first=Danial |date=11 March 2026 |title=Bayerns 6:1 bei Atalanta: Erst dieses grandiose Spiel, doch nun diese Sorgen |url=https://www.spiegel.de/sport/fussball/champions-league-fc-bayern-muenchen-siegt-6-1-bei-atalanta-bergamo-grosses-spiel-grosse-tragik-a-78861c03-800e-4eeb-8eda-bc9f9917f36d |access-date=5 April 2026 |work=Der Spiegel |language=de |issn=2195-1349}}</ref> forcing him to miss the international break.<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 March 2026 |title=Darum nominiert Nagelsmann Musiala nicht |url=https://www.sport1.de/news/fussball/dfb-team/2026/03/entscheidung-bei-musiala-gefallen |access-date=5 April 2026 |website=SPORT1 |language=de}}</ref> He returned to the pitch on 4 April in a 3–2 away win over [[SC Freiburg|Freiburg]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 April 2026 |title=„Dafür hat er genug Zeit“: Bayern-Boss Eberl kontert Nagelsmann in WM-Debatte um Musiala |url=https://www.absolutfussball.com/deutschland/fc-bayern-muenchen/musiala-bayern-boss-eberl-widerspricht-nagelsmann-in-wm-frage-um-zr-94248765.html |access-date=5 April 2026 |website=www.absolutfussball.com |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=4 April 2026 |title=Freiburg gegen Bayern 04.04.2026 -Bundesliga Liveticker |url=https://www.kicker.de/freiburg-gegen-bayern-2026-bundesliga-5050996/ticker |url-status=live |access-date=5 April 2026 |website=Kicker}}</ref> Three days later, he featured in a 2–1 away win against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in the Champions League quarter-final, getting subbed on in the 69th minute for [[Serge Gnabry]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 April 2026 |title=Real Madrid gegen Bayern München Liveticker |url=https://www.kicker.de/real-madrid-gegen-bayern-2026-champions-league-5195133/ticker |url-status=live |access-date=8 April 2026 |website=kicker}}</ref> On 11 April, Musiala set Bayern's all-time record from [[1971–72 FC Bayern Munich season|1971–72]] for the most scored goals in a single season, by scoring the 101st goal of the season in a 5–0 victory over [[FC St. Pauli|St. Pauli]]. The record would be broken in the same match by [[Leon Goretzka]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=BR24Sport |title=Goretzka erzielt Rekordtor: 29 Spiele, 102 Tore - Bayern knacken Bundesliga-Torrekord |url=https://www.sportschau.de/regional/br/br-102-fc-bayern-treffer-leon-goretzka-knackt-bundesliga-torrekord-102.html |access-date=11 April 2026 |website=sportschau.de |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=11 April 2026 |title=FC St. Pauli - FC Bayern München (Spielbericht) |url=https://fcbayern.com/de/spiele/profis/bundesliga/2025-2026/fc-st-pauli-fc-bayern-muenchen-11-04-2026/spielbericht |url-status=live |access-date=11 April 2026 |website=FC Bayern}}</ref> Four days later, he became the youngest German player to reach 50 Champions League appearances in a 4–3 victory over Real Madrid, surpassing [[Thomas Müller]], aged 23 years and 48 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/02a4-205f25ee8b2f-a897e762ffe8-1000--champions-league-quarter-finals-key-stats-and-what-to-look-o/ |title=Champions League quarter-finals: Key stats and what to look out for in the second legs |publisher=UEFA |date=15 April 2026 }}</ref> He would assist the decisive 3–3 in the 89th minute by [[Luis Díaz (footballer, born 1997)|Luis Díaz]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bayern 4-3 Real Madrid (Apr 15, 2026) Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/401862891/real-madrid-bayern-munich |access-date=16 April 2026 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
Musiala, who was also eligible to play for [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] via his father, represented both England and Germany at youth international level.<ref name="bundesliga"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.dfb.de/datencenter/personen/jamal-musiala/spieler | title = Jamal Musiala - Spielerprofil |publisher=German Football Association | language = de | access-date = 13 December 2020}}</ref>

===Youth===
[[File:Jamal Musiala October 2019.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Musiala with England in 2019]]
In November 2020, Musiala was called up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] squad for the first time for their [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2020/nov/06/england-mu21s-squad-named-for-november-games-with-albania-and-andorra-061120|title= Two new faces included in the England MU21s squad for games with Andorra and Albania |publisher=The Football Association |date=6 November 2020|access-date=6 November 2020}}</ref> He made his U21 debut as a substitute during a 3–1 victory over the [[Andorra national under-21 football team|Andorra U21s]] at [[Molineux Stadium]] on 13 November 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54934110|title= England U21 3-1 Andorra U21 |website=BBC Sport |date=13 November 2020|access-date=13 November 2020}}</ref> He scored his first under-21 goal during a 5–0 win over [[Albania national under-21 football team|Albania]] also at Molineux Stadium on 17 November 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 November 2020 |title=England U21 5-0 Albania U21 |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54979326 |access-date=17 November 2020}}</ref> After choosing to represent England's U21s, the [[German Football Association|German football association]] indicated that they had stopped pursuing Musiala, with German youth team coach [[:de:Meikel Schönweitz|Meikel Schönweitz]] stating: "He [Musiala] has clearly signaled to us that he currently sees his future with the English national teams. We accept his decision and wish him all the best for his sporting career."<ref name= "Goal">{{cite news |title=Bayern wonderkid Musiala 'sees his future' with England amid international tussle with Germany |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/bayern-wonderkid-musiala-sees-his-future-with-england-amid/1n0bofp7ggojr16c8jupqeejg9 |access-date=2 February 2021 |website=Goal.com |publisher=Perform Group |date=12 November 2020}}</ref> Musiala had previously indicated that he felt more comfortable playing for England at youth level than for Germany, as he grew up as a footballer at Chelsea with other English players, whereas for Germany, he did not know any of the other players.<ref name = "DW">{{cite news |title=Bayern Munich's Jamal Musiala in Germany-England tug-of-war |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bayern-munichs-jamal-musiala-in-germany-england-tug-of-war/a-56406533 |access-date=2 February 2021 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |date=1 February 2021}}</ref>

===Senior===
[[File:Jamal Musiala WC2022.jpg|thumb|upright|Musiala with Germany at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]]]]
On 24 February 2021, Musiala announced he had decided to represent his mother's nation and his birth nation Germany at the international level.<ref name="right21">{{Cite web|title=Jamal Musiala exclusive: Why it's the right decision to play for Germany |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/2408268/2021/02/24/jamal-musiala-bayern-munich-exclusive-why-right-decision-to-play-for-germany-england/|date=24 February 2021|access-date=24 February 2021|website=The Athletic}}</ref><ref name="feels21">{{Cite web|title=Musiala: "Entscheidung fühlt sich 100 Prozent richtig an"|trans-title=Musiala: "Decision feels 100 percent right"|url=https://www.sportschau.de/fussball/bundesliga/jamal-musiala-nationalmannschaft-interview-100.html|author=Philipp Nagel |date=24 February 2021|access-date=24 February 2021|website=Sportschau |language=de}}</ref> He subsequently received his first call up to the senior team for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] in March 2021,<ref>{{cite web | title = Start ins EM-Jahr: Musiala und Wirtz erstmals im DFB-Team | url = https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/start-ins-em-jahr-musiala-und-wirtz-erstmals-im-dfb-team-225461/ | website = dfb.de | language = de | date = 19 March 2021 | access-date = 25 March 2021}}</ref> making his debut on 25 March 2021 as a 79th minute substitute in a 3–0 win against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Germany vs. Iceland 3–0 |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2021/03/25/europe/wc-qualifying-europe/germany/iceland/3430239/ |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=28 March 2021}}</ref> According to former Germany coach [[Joachim Löw]], he promised Musiala a call-up for the UEFA Euro 2020 if he chooses Germany over England. Löw said "It was the only time in my time as national team coach that I made a promise to a player: Even though he wasn't a regular at Bayern, I told him that if he chose us, he would definitely be playing at Euro 2020 in the summer."<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 November 2024 |title=Löw reveals how he persuaded Musiala to play for Germany instead of England |url=https://bulinews.com/low-reveals-how-persuaded-musiala-play-for-germany-instead-england |access-date=16 December 2024 |website=Bundesliga News in English |language=en}}</ref>

====Euro 2020====
On 19 May 2021, Musiala was selected to the German squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kicker.de/em-kader-offiziell-loew-beruft-mueller-hummels-und-volland-804642/artikel|title=EM-Kader offiziell: Löw beruft Müller, Hummels und Volland|date=19 May 2021|website=kicker |publisher=Olympia-Verlag |language=de|access-date=19 May 2021}}</ref> On 23 June 2021, he became the youngest German player to feature in a major tournament for the Germany national team in a 2–2 draw with [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], aged 18 years and 117 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/19692/12340079/germany-2-2-hungary-leon-goretzkas-late-equaliser-sees-germany-survive-euro-2020-scare |title=Germany 2-2 Hungary: Leon Goretzka's late equaliser sees Germany survive Euro 2020 scare |website=Sky Sports |date=23 June 2021 }}</ref> During the match, Musiala set up [[Leon Goretzka]]'s late equalizer which sent Germany through to the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout phase#Round of 16|round of 16]]. He was brought on as a substitute in the round of 16 game against [[England national football team|England]], which Germany lost.<ref>{{cite web |last=Glendenning |first=Barry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2021/jun/29/england-v-germany-euro-2020-last-16-live-score-updates |title=England 2-0 Germany: Euro 2020, last 16 – as it happened |work=The Guardian |date=29 June 2021 }}</ref>

====2022 World Cup qualification====
On 11 October 2021, Musiala scored his first senior international goal in a 4–0 win over [[North Macedonia national football team|North Macedonia]], becoming the second-youngest player to score for the Germany national team, aged 18 years and 227 days, only behind [[Marius Hiller]], aged 17 years and 241 days, in 1910.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/north-macedonia-germany-live-world-cup-qualifying-line-ups-stats-musiala-sane-17552 |title=Jamal Musiala among the goals in North Macedonia as Germany qualify for Qatar 2022 |website=Bundesliga |date=11 October 2021 }}</ref>

====2022 World Cup====
On 10 November 2022, Musiala received a call-up for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/flick-beruft-moukoko-fuellkrug-und-goetze-in-wm-kader-245974/ |title=Flick beruft Moukoko, Füllkrug und Götze in WM-Kader |trans-title=Flick names Moukoko, Füllkrug and Götze to World Cup squad |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=10 November 2022 |access-date=10 November 2022 |language=de}}</ref> On 23 November, he made his World Cup debut by starting against [[Japan national football team|Japan]], to become the first German teenager to feature in the competition since 1958, and the fourth youngest German player, aged 19 years and 270 days, in all World Cup participations, only behind: [[Karl-Heinz Schnellinger]], [[Leopold Neumer]] and [[Edmund Conen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sport1.de/news/fussball/wm/2022/11/wm-2022-deutschland-japan-historischer-einsatz-von-jamal-musiala |title=Historischer Einsatz von Musiala |website=sport1.de |language=de |date=23 November 2022 }}</ref> In the same match, [[Youssoufa Moukoko]] was subbed on in the 90th minute, to be the youngest ever, and Musiala then became the fifth.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kicker.de/moukoko-knackt-64-jahre-alten-rekord-musiala-fuenfter-926905/artikel |title=Moukoko knackt 64 Jahre alten Rekord - Musiala Fünfter |website=[[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]] |language=de |date=23 November 2022 }}</ref> On 1 December, he completed 13 dribbles, two shy of [[Jay-Jay Okocha]]'s record of 15 in [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]], in a 4–2 win over [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], yet Germany were eliminated in the group stage for the second successive World Cup as they finished third in their group.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/football/news-gives-us-lionel-messi-vibes-fans-believe-germany-star-doesn-t-deserve-go-fifa-world-cup-performance-costa-rica |title="Gives us Lionel Messi vibes" – Fans believe Germany star doesn't deserve to go out of the FIFA World Cup after performance against Costa Rica |website=Sportskeeda |date=1 December 2022 }}</ref>

====Euro 2024====
On 7 June 2024, Musiala was named in Germany's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]] on home soil.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://olympics.com/en/news/uefa-euro-2024-all-squads-and-players-full-list|title=UEFA Euro 2024: All squads and players full list|date=7 June 2024|access-date=7 June 2024|website=Olympics.com}}</ref> On 14 June, he was awarded Player of the Match in the opening encounter against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b22000e24bf-9d79cc6fc92b-1000--every-euro-2024-player-of-the-match/ |title=Every EURO 2024 Player of the Match |publisher=UEFA |date=14 June 2024 }}</ref> where he scored a goal in a 5–1 victory, becoming the second youngest German player to score in the tournament, 67 days older than his teammate [[Florian Wirtz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/lite/story/1.7235849 |title=Host Germany kicks off Euro with 4-goal victory over 10-man Scotland |publisher=CBC |date=14 June 2024 }}</ref> He scored in the 68th minute for Germany against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in the round of 16 game on 29 June.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jones |first=Michael |date=27 June 2024 |title=Germany v Denmark LIVE: Final score and result after sublime Jamal Musiala strikes for Euro 2024 hosts |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/germany-denmark-live-stream-score-result-euro-2024-b2570061.html |access-date=30 June 2024 |work=The Independent |language=en}}</ref> On 5 July, Musiala played the full game as Germany were eliminated by eventual champions [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in the quarter-finals. With three goals in the tournament, Musiala was awarded the [[UEFA European Championship awards#Golden Boot|Golden Boot]] in a six-way tie.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/football/story/_/id/40558317/euro-2024-golden-boot-harry-kane-dani-olmo-6-winners |title=Euro 2024 Golden Boot: Harry Kane, Dani Olmo among 6 winners |website=ESPN|date=14 July 2024|access-date=15 July 2024}}</ref>

====FIFA World Cup 2026====
On 21 May 2026, he was selected in Germany’s 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/news/bundestrainer-nagelsmann-gibt-wm-kader-bekannt|title=Bundestrainer Nagelsmann gibt WM-Kader bekannt|publisher=[[German Football Association]]|language=de|date=21 May 2026|access-date=21 May 2026}}</ref>

==Style of play==
[[File:2022 FIFA World Cup Germany 1–2 Japan - (8) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Musiala in 2022]]
A versatile player, Musiala can play in any attacking or midfield position, though he prefers to play on the left side of the field.<ref name="Hodson">{{Cite web |last=Hodson |first=Tony |title=Jamal Musiala: Bundesliga Player Watch |url=https://www.coachesvoice.com/cv/jamal-musiala-bayern-munich-chelsea-germany/ |access-date=11 July 2022 |website=The Coaches' Voice}}</ref> Musiala is known for his close-control dribbling and can beat opponents with feints and tricks, which has earned him the nickname "Bambi".<ref name=":2" /> He is also known for his vision and accurate passing. [[Hansi Flick]], his former coach at Bayern Munich, stated, "He has a great eye and feeling for choosing the right spaces. He is very confident on the ball and can play well between the lines."<ref name="Hodson"/> Musiala has been widely described as one of the best young players in the world.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=1 April 2024 |title=The best players in the world - ranked |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/best-players-in-the-world |access-date=5 August 2024 |website=90min.com |language=en-GB}}</ref>{{refn|<ref>{{Cite web |last=Veth |first=Manuel |title=Jamal Musiala: Is The Bayern Munich Star The Best In The Bundesliga? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/manuelveth/2022/10/22/jamal-musiala-is-the-bayern-munich-star-the-best-in-the-bundesliga/ |access-date=19 February 2023 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Jamal Musiala: Who is the Bayern Munich and Germany teen sensation? |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/who-is-jamal-musiala-bayern-munich-s-half-england-germany-star-of-the-future-11525 |access-date=19 February 2024 |website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title="Jude Bellingham and Jamal Musiala the standout players in 2022" - Philipp Lahm |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/jude-bellingham-jamal-musiala-best-players-in-2022-philipp-lahm-interview-22102 |access-date=19 February 2023 |website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Telford |first=Stuart |date=1 December 2022 |title=Jamal Musiala, the shy 'Bambi' who became the world's best teenager |url=https://www.footballtransfers.com/us/transfer-news/de-bundesliga/2022/12/jamal-musiala-shy-bambi-world-s-best-teenager-us |access-date=19 February 2023 |website=www.footballtransfers.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Germany's own Messi? Jamal Musiala arrives at the World Cup as a genuine Ballon d'Or contender {{!}} Goal.com |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/germany-own-messi-musiala-world-cup-ballon-dor-contender/blt87ed762d841f37c2 |access-date=19 February 2023 |website=www.goal.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/best-players-in-the-world |website=www.90min.com |title=The best young players in the world - ranked |date=7 June 2024 |access-date= 14 June 2024}}</ref>}}<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |title=Jamal Musiala isn't just Euro 2024's best young player, he's the best overall so far |url=https://www.foxsports.com/stories/soccer/jamal-musiala-isnt-just-euro-2024s-best-young-player-he-is-the-best-overall-so-far |access-date=5 August 2024 |website=FOX Sports |language=en-US}}</ref>

